show_command_info() {
    case "$1" in

        # NETWORK
        whois|whois_lookup)
            cat <<'EOF'
Performs a WHOIS lookup on a domain or IP address.

WHOIS is a query and response protocol used to retrieve information about registered domain names, IP addresses, and autonomous systems.
This command queries the WHOIS database to return ownership details, registration dates, expiry dates, name servers, and registrar information.
Useful for investigating domain ownership, checking domain availability, or gathering reconnaissance data on a target.
Be aware that many domains use WHOIS privacy protection services, which may obscure the true owner's details.
This script uses the whois utility, available on most Unix-like systems.

https://www.iana.org/whois / https://github.com/nicowillis/whois
EOF
            ;;

        ping)
            cat <<'EOF'
Sends ICMP echo requests to a host to test network connectivity and measure round-trip time.
Ping is one of the most fundamental network diagnostic tools, used to determine whether a host is reachable and how long packets take to travel to it and back.

This command reports packet loss, latency (in milliseconds), and jitter — key indicators of network health.
Note that some hosts and firewalls are configured to block ICMP packets, so a non-response does not always mean the host is offline.
Useful for basic connectivity testing, latency diagnostics, and detecting packet loss on a link.
This script uses the system ping utility, built into all major operating systems.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ping_(networking_utility)

EOF
            ;;

        traceroute|trace)
            cat <<'EOF'
Traces the network path (hops) packets take to reach a destination host.

Traceroute works by sending packets with incrementally increasing TTL (Time To Live) values, causing each router along the path to return an ICMP "time exceeded" message, revealing its IP address and latency.
This command is essential for diagnosing where network delays or failures occur between your machine and a target.
Each hop displayed represents a router or gateway the packet passed through, along with its round-trip time.
Some hops may appear as * * * if the router is configured to not respond to traceroute probes.
This script uses traceroute. 

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traceroute
EOF
            ;;

        dns|dns_info)
            cat <<'EOF'
Performs DNS lookups and retrieves detailed DNS record information for a domain.

DNS (Domain Name System) is the internet's phonebook, translating human-readable domain names into IP addresses.
This command queries DNS records including A, AAAA, MX, NS, TXT, CNAME, SOA, and PTR records, giving a full picture of a domain's DNS configuration.
Useful for diagnosing DNS propagation issues, verifying mail server configurations, or performing reconnaissance on a domain's infrastructure.
DNS information is publicly accessible by design, making it a valuable starting point for network investigations.

This script uses dig (DNS lookup utility) and/or nslookup, available via the dnsutils package.

https://www.isc.org/bind/ / https://linux.die.net/man/1/dig
EOF
            ;;

        ip|get_ip)
            cat <<'EOF'
Retrieves your current public and/or local IP address information.

Your public IP address is the address visible to the outside internet, assigned by your ISP or VPN provider. Your local IP is your address within your local network (LAN).
This command fetches both, along with geolocation metadata such as country, city, ISP, and ASN (Autonomous System Number) associated with your public IP.
Knowing your public IP is essential when configuring firewalls, port forwarding, or verifying whether a VPN or proxy is active and masking your real address.
This script queries public IP APIs of ipinfo.io, and uses ip addr or ifconfig for local addresses.

https://ipinfo.io 

EOF
            ;;

        osint|ip_osint)
            cat <<'EOF'
Performs Open Source Intelligence (OSINT) gathering on an IP address or domain.

OSINT refers to the collection and analysis of information from publicly available sources. For IP addresses and domains, this includes geolocation, ASN data, abuse reports, open ports, reverse DNS, and historical WHOIS records.
This command aggregates data from multiple public threat intelligence and lookup services to build a comprehensive profile of a target IP or domain.
Useful for investigating suspicious connections, attributing malicious traffic, or performing pre-engagement reconnaissance in authorized penetration tests.
Always ensure you have proper authorization before conducting OSINT on any target. This tool is intended for defensive and educational use.
This script integrates tools of ipinfo.io.

https://ipinfo.io 

EOF
            ;;

        inspect_cert)
            cat <<'EOF'
Inspects and displays the SSL/TLS certificate details of a remote host.

SSL/TLS certificates are used to authenticate the identity of a server and establish encrypted connections. They contain information such as the issuer, subject, validity period, Subject Alternative Names (SANs), and the public key algorithm used.
This command connects to a target host and retrieves its certificate chain, displaying all relevant fields in a human-readable format.
Useful for verifying certificate validity, checking expiry dates, auditing cipher configurations, or investigating suspicious HTTPS endpoints.
An expired or mis-issued certificate can indicate misconfiguration or a potential man-in-the-middle attack.

This script uses OpenSSL's s_client command to retrieve and parse certificate information.

https://www.openssl.org/ / https://github.com/openssl/openssl

EOF
            ;;

        tor_connect)
            cat <<'EOF'
Routes your network traffic through the Tor anonymity network.

Tor (The Onion Router) anonymizes internet traffic by encrypting it and routing it through a series of volunteer-operated relays around the world, making it extremely difficult to trace the origin of the traffic.
This command configures your system or a specific application to use Tor as a SOCKS5 proxy, masking your real IP address and bypassing censorship or geo-restrictions.
Tor is widely used by journalists, activists, security researchers, and privacy-conscious users. However, it significantly reduces connection speed due to the multi-hop routing.

Note: Tor does not make you fully anonymous on its own. Application-level leaks (cookies, WebRTC, DNS) can still expose your identity if not properly handled.
This script uses the Tor daemon and optionally proxychains to tunnel traffic through the Tor network.

https://www.torproject.org / https://github.com/torproject/tor
EOF
            ;;

        maigret_search)
            cat <<'EOF'
Searches for a username across hundreds of websites and social networks using Maigret.

Maigret is an OSINT tool that takes a single username and checks its existence across a large database of websites, generating a detailed report of where that username is registered.
This command is useful for investigating a person's online footprint, tracking usernames across platforms, or gathering intelligence during authorized investigations.
Maigret can detect accounts on social media platforms, forums, gaming networks, dating sites, developer communities, and many more — all from a single username query.
Results are presented as a structured report and can be exported to HTML, PDF, or JSON formats.

Always use this tool ethically and only on usernames you are authorized to investigate. Unauthorized OSINT can have legal implications.

This script uses the Maigret Python tool: https://github.com/soxoj/maigret
https://github.com/soxoj/maigret
EOF
            ;;

        # SYSTEM
        update_apps)
            cat <<'EOF'
Updates all installed system packages and applications to their latest versions.

Keeping software up to date is one of the most critical security practices. The majority of successful cyberattacks exploit known vulnerabilities in outdated software for which patches already exist.
This command runs a full system update using the appropriate package manager for your OS (apt, brew, dnf, pacman, etc.), fetching the latest package lists and upgrading all outdated software.
It may also update Flatpak, Snap, pip, or other package ecosystems if present on your system.
Regular updates reduce your attack surface and ensure you benefit from the latest performance improvements and bug fixes.
It is recommended to run this command at least weekly, or automate it via a scheduled task.
EOF
