        setup_clamav)
            cat <<'EOF'
Installs and configures ClamAV, an open-source antivirus engine for detecting malware and malicious files.

ClamAV is a widely used antivirus solution for Unix-like systems, capable of scanning files, directories, email attachments, and archives for known malware signatures.
This command installs ClamAV and its daemon, updates the virus definition database via freshclam, and optionally configures scheduled scans using cron.
While ClamAV is not a replacement for a full endpoint security suite, it provides a solid baseline of protection against known threats, particularly for file servers and mail gateways.

The virus definition database is updated regularly by the ClamAV community and should be refreshed frequently to maintain effectiveness against new threats.
ClamAV can be integrated with other tools such as SpamAssassin and Postfix for mail filtering pipelines.

https://www.clamav.net / https://github.com/Cisco-Talos/clamav

EOF
            ;;

        setup_usbguard)
            cat <<'EOF'
Installs and configures USBGuard, a framework for protecting your system against unauthorized USB devices.

USB-based attacks (such as BadUSB, rubber ducky attacks, and rogue HID devices) are a well-known physical attack vector that can bypass traditional network-based security controls.
USBGuard enforces a policy-based whitelist of allowed USB devices. Any device not explicitly permitted by the policy will be blocked when plugged in, preventing malicious or unauthorized peripherals from interacting with your system.

This command installs USBGuard, generates an initial policy based on currently connected trusted devices, and enables the daemon to enforce the policy at boot.
Particularly useful in high-security environments, shared workstations, or systems that should never accept unknown USB peripherals.
Policies can be customized to allow or block devices based on vendor ID, product ID, serial number, and device class.

https://usbguard.github.io / https://github.com/USBGuard/usbguard

EOF
            ;;

        setup_ufw)
            cat <<'EOF'
Installs and configures UFW (Uncomplicated Firewall), a user-friendly frontend for managing iptables firewall rules.

A firewall is a critical component of any secure system, controlling which network traffic is allowed in and out of your machine based on defined rules.
UFW simplifies the management of Linux's powerful but complex iptables rule system, providing intuitive commands for allowing, denying, and limiting traffic by port, protocol, and IP address.

This command installs UFW, applies a secure default policy (deny all incoming, allow all outgoing), and enables common rules such as allowing SSH while blocking all other inbound connections.
Properly configured firewall rules significantly reduce your attack surface by ensuring only explicitly permitted services are accessible from the network.
UFW also supports rate limiting to protect against brute-force attacks and can log blocked connection attempts for auditing purposes.

https://help.ubuntu.com/community/UFW / https://github.com/chaifeng/ufw-docker

EOF
            ;;

        # PRIVACY & SECURITY
        set|secure_empty_trash)
            cat <<'EOF'
Securely deletes the contents of your Trash by overwriting files before removal.

Standard file deletion in most operating systems simply removes the file's reference in the filesystem, leaving the actual data on disk until it is overwritten by new data — making it trivially recoverable with common forensic tools.
This command overwrites the contents of trashed files with random data (multiple passes) before deleting them, making recovery significantly more difficult or practically impossible.
Secure deletion is particularly important before selling, donating, or discarding storage media, and when handling sensitive documents.

This tool uses SRM a security uttility to securely delete files, which implements the Gutmann method of overwriting data multiple times with different patterns.

Note: On SSDs and flash storage, secure overwriting is less reliable due to wear leveling and over-provisioning. Full-disk encryption is the recommended solution for SSDs.
This script uses tools such as shred, srm, or secure-delete depending on your OS.

https://sourceforge.net/projects/srm 

EOF
            ;;

        sofc|secure_overwrite_free_space)
            cat <<'EOF'
Overwrites all free (unallocated) space on a disk to eliminate traces of previously deleted files.

When files are deleted normally, their data remains on disk in unallocated sectors until overwritten. Forensic tools can recover this data — sometimes months or years after deletion.
This command fills all free space on the target filesystem with random or zero data, effectively wiping any recoverable remnants of previously deleted files without affecting currently existing data.
This is useful after bulk deletion of sensitive files, before transferring ownership of a device, or as part of a periodic privacy maintenance routine.
The process can be time-consuming depending on the size of the drive and the number of overwrite passes selected.
As with secure file deletion, this is less reliable on SSDs due to how flash storage manages data internally. Full-disk encryption remains the gold standard.
This script uses tools such as sfill (from the secure-delete suite) or dd.

https://sourceforge.net/projects/srm / https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/shred-invocation.html

EOF
            ;;

