Removes temporary files and directories from common system and application temp locations.

Temporary files accumulate over time from system operations, application crashes, software installations, and normal usage. Left unchecked, they consume disk space and may contain sensitive data fragments from past sessions.
This command clears temp directories such as /tmp, /var/tmp, ~/.cache, and application-specific temp folders, safely removing files that are no longer needed by any running process.
Regular temp file cleanup reduces disk usage, can improve system performance, and limits the amount of sensitive residual data an attacker or forensic investigator could access.

The script checks for files in use before deletion to avoid disrupting active processes.
This is a non-destructive operation targeting only known temporary locations — it does not touch user documents or application data.

https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd-tmpfiles.html

